courses.name: Strategy and Statecraft: War and Diplomacy in European History

primaryOrg.name: John H. Daniels Faculty of Architecture, Landscape, & Design

cmCourseInfo.description: An analysis of the development of the international system, from 1648 to 1945, which highlights the role of war as an instrument of national policy, as a determinant of the system of states and as a threat to international society.
cmCourseInfo.title: Strategy and Statecraft: War and Diplomacy in European History
cmCourseInfo.exclusionsText: HIS100Y1, HIS101Y1, HIS102Y1, HIS106Y1, HIS107Y1, HIS108Y1, HIS109Y1, HIS110Y1

primaryOrg.name: John H. Daniels Faculty of Architecture, Landscape, & Design

cmCourseInfo.description: The political, social, economic, and intellectual history of continental Europe. Development of royal absolutism, social change and the crisis of the ancient regime, the Enlightenment, the French Revolution, the Napoleonic era.
cmCourseInfo.title: Early Modern Europe, 1648-1815

primaryOrg.name: John H. Daniels Faculty of Architecture, Landscape, & Design

cmCourseInfo.description: This course introduces key issues in Canadian history and foundational principles of historical analysis. It is primarily designed for potential History majors/specialists. It is not a comprehensive survey. Examples serve to deepen analysis and introduce important methods and debates, preparing students for upper year courses in Canadian history.
cmCourseInfo.title: Critical Issues in Canadian History

primaryOrg.name: John H. Daniels Faculty of Architecture, Landscape, & Design

cmCourseInfo.description: A critical history of the place we today call China from prehistoric times to the 21st century, tracing shifting borders, identities, governments, and cultures while challenging any singular definition of "China."
cmCourseInfo.title: History of China

sections.name: LEC0101
sections.subTitle: Mobility and the Making of European Empires in Africa

primaryOrg.name: John H. Daniels Faculty of Architecture, Landscape, & Design

cmCourseInfo.description: Selected topics on a specific period, aspect or themes in African history. Topics in any given year depend on the instructor.
cmCourseInfo.title: Topics in African History

courses.name: Catholic Asia in the Early Modern Era, 1500-1800

primaryOrg.name: John H. Daniels Faculty of Architecture, Landscape, & Design

cmCourseInfo.description: This course examines the impact of Catholicism in Asia, from its introduction to its relevance in the contemporary global order. Students will be introduced to how Catholicism and the technologies accompanying it affected historical transitions in local communities in Asia as well as how the growth of these communities has affected the global Catholic Church.
cmCourseInfo.title: Catholic Asia in the Early Modern Era, 1500-1800
cmCourseInfo.prerequisitesText: 1.0 credit in European or Asian history. Students who do not meet the prerequisite are encouraged to contact the Department.

notes.name: Course Note
notes.content:
Delivery Instructions

Students must have a reliable internet connection to be able to access lectures and Quercus online.

primaryOrg.name: John H. Daniels Faculty of Architecture, Landscape, & Design

cmCourseInfo.description: This course explores the rise of modern intelligence over the long 20th century, from Anglo-Russian imperial competition before World War I through to the post-9/11 era. Students will study the contribution of intelligence services to victories and defeats in war, peace, and the grey areas in between. The course will also examine the relationship between intelligence services and society.
cmCourseInfo.title: History of Modern Intelligence
cmCourseInfo.recommendedPreparation: HIS103Y1 or an equivalent introduction to modern international relations

sections.name: LEC5101
sections.subTitle: An Empire of Travel: British World Tourism in the Long Nineteenth Century

primaryOrg.name: John H. Daniels Faculty of Architecture, Landscape, & Design

cmCourseInfo.description: An in-depth examination of historical issues. Content in any given year depends on instructor. See History website for more details.
cmCourseInfo.title: Topics in History
cmCourseInfo.prerequisitesText: 14.0 credits, including 2.0 HIS credits excluding HIS262H1. Further prerequisites vary from year to year, consult the department.
